And there'll be no one here to take care of him.

514
00:44:14,750 --> 00:44:17,950
Well, Charlie's in school, so...

515
00:44:18,900 --> 00:44:20,340
Who's Charlie?

516
00:44:20,340 --> 00:44:22,240
My boyfriend, Charlie.

517
00:44:23,310 --> 00:44:25,150
Do you have
a girlfriend?

518
00:44:25,900 --> 00:44:28,550
- What makes you think I want one?
- Just guessing.

519
00:44:34,650 --> 00:44:36,600
- This isn't him.
- What?

520
00:44:36,650 --> 00:44:38,000
Willy. Right here.

521
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:40,550
- Sure, it is.
- Willy's fin is flopped over.

522
00:44:41,100 --> 00:44:42,950
That's what happens in captivity.

523
00:44:43,190 --> 00:44:44,200
Why?

524
00:44:44,400 --> 00:44:48,330
Nobody knows.  Maybe they need
more room to really swim.

525
00:44:48,650 --> 00:44:51,750
Then how come Mr. Dial
won't build Willy a bigger tank?

526
00:44:51,800 --> 00:44:55,450
Because Dial thinks he can treat
a wild animals like a commodity.

527
00:44:55,550 --> 00:44:56,950
What's that?

528
00:44:57,900 --> 00:45:00,650
Just a big word Dial likes to use.

529
00:45:02,800 --> 00:45:08,350
Actually, It means that Dial  won't
build Willy a bigger pool...

530
00:45:08,350 --> 00:45:11,250
...unless he thinks he can make
more money off of him.

531
00:45:13,700 --> 00:45:15,000
How'd you like
to help me with that?

532
00:45:17,200 --> 00:45:18,600
Yeah, sure!

533
00:45:18,650 --> 00:45:21,000
Most orcas love to play
around and do tricks.

534
00:45:21,400 --> 00:45:23,600
They like the stimulation.

535
00:45:24,800 --> 00:45:25,800
[snorts]

536
00:45:26,500 --> 00:45:27,900
Can he see me underwater?

537
00:45:27,900 --> 00:45:30,650
Sure, he can.  He can hear you, too,
from anywhere in this whole tank.

538
00:45:31,500 --> 00:45:34,900
Now, this, young man,
is a target.

539
00:45:36,150 --> 00:45:39,250
Willy's supposed
to respond to it, follow it.

540
00:45:39,600 --> 00:45:42,570
And when we work on tricks or behaviors,
we reward him with fish.

541
00:45:42,800 --> 00:45:44,250
Now, what we’re
gonna try to do is...

542
00:45:44,500 --> 00:45:48,100
See if we can get Willy’s nose
to touch the end of this target.

543
00:45:48,100 --> 00:45:49,100
Ok?
Ok.

544
00:45:49,150 --> 00:45:51,000
Move out there.

545
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:53,300
You're doing pretty great.

546
00:45:53,400 --> 00:45:54,850
Thanks.

547
00:45:56,550 --> 00:45:58,000
Thank he with a fish!

548
00:46:00,050 --> 00:46:01,850
There you go, Willy.

549
00:46:03,800 --> 00:46:06,800
He likes that fish, doesn't he?

550
00:46:07,900 --> 00:46:09,250
Roll on over.

551
00:46:10,300 --> 00:46:14,930
Orcas love to be touched, petted,
hugged, anything like that.

552
00:46:16,350 --> 00:46:18,900
Oh, they love to have
their tongue stroked.

553
00:46:19,100 --> 00:46:20,100
Wait a minute...

554
00:46:20,100 --> 00:46:24,800
You want me to take my hand,
stick it in his mouth, and rub his tongue?

555
00:46:24,850 --> 00:46:26,200
Yeah, eventually.

556
00:46:26,200 --> 00:46:27,700
I don't think so.

557
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:31,350
You'll learn to read him.
You'll be able to do it.

558
00:46:36,600 --> 00:46:37,950
What's this?

559
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:40,550
Thought you might want to know
what we're dealing with here.

560
00:46:40,550 --> 00:46:41,700
My father
gave it to me.

561
00:46:41,800 --> 00:46:42,450
Thanks.

562
00:46:42,450 --> 00:46:44,550
It's Haida.
What?

563
00:46:44,750 --> 00:46:47,150
"Haida" is the name of my people.

564
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:51,700
300 years ago, there were so many
fish in the water,

565
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:54,600
...my people only had to spend
one day a week gathering food.

566
00:46:54,600 --> 00:46:56,900
And everybody ate like kings.

567
00:46:57,100 --> 00:47:00,850
- What did they do the rest of the time?
- Carved and painted totems,

568
00:47:00,900 --> 00:47:04,250
...made music, told stories, made babies.

569
00:47:04,300 --> 00:47:07,460
Sounds good to me.

570
00:47:10,200 --> 00:47:11,450
<i>Skaana.</i>

571
00:47:11,900 --> 00:47:14,000
It's the Haida word
for "whale".

572
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:20,250
Natsaclane was a Haida who lived a long
time ago, before there were orca whales.

573
00:47:20,350 --> 00:47:24,200
Hunting fish with the other warriors,
young Natsaclane lost his way

574
00:47:24,200 --> 00:47:25,600
...and found himself all alone.

575
00:47:25,600 --> 00:47:29,200
While he was searching,
a fierce storm began.

576
00:47:29,350 --> 00:47:32,000
Natsaclane couldn't find
shelter anywhere.

577
00:47:32,100 --> 00:47:34,800
The otters came and took him
way down deep under the water...

578
00:47:34,800 --> 00:47:37,100
...where he was safe
for the night.

579
00:47:37,200 --> 00:47:42,200
After the storm, Natsaclane again
searched for the braves.

580
00:47:42,250 --> 00:47:45,800
But all he found was a huge log.

581
00:47:46,300 --> 00:47:49,300
He began carving
a great beast on the log...

582
00:47:49,300 --> 00:47:51,800
...and tried carrying it to the ocean.

583
00:47:51,900 --> 00:47:54,750
Finally, he found some water,
but it wasn't the ocean.

584
00:47:55,000 --> 00:47:58,300
The great carving sank to the bottom
of this pool and disappeared.

585
00:47:58,750 --> 00:48:02,200
Natsaclane sat
and watched and waited...

586
00:48:02,200 --> 00:48:04,750
...and said a prayer
he never heard before.

587
00:48:04,900 --> 00:48:07,800
<i>Sa-la-na a-yoong I-asis.</i>

588
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:11,000
<i>Sa-la-na a-yoong I-asis.</i>

589
00:48:11,100 --> 00:48:14,250
He kept saying this prayer.
It's so weird!

590
00:48:14,500 --> 00:48:16,400
He'd never heard it before.

591
00:48:16,500 --> 00:48:20,800
Then it really got crazy, because
the water started flying out,

592
00:48:20,800 --> 00:48:23,950
...and all this commotion
started happening.

593
00:48:24,550 --> 00:48:27,600
And out of the water
came the carving.

594
00:48:27,750 --> 00:48:29,250
And it wasn't a carving.

595
00:48:29,450 --> 00:48:31,250
It was a whale, like Willy.

596
00:48:31,250 --> 00:48:33,950
He flew all the way down
to the ocean, like a bird,

597
00:48:34,150 --> 00:48:38,500
...and Natsaclane, he went after him,
down to the beach.

598
00:48:38,500 --> 00:48:41,850
And he got on his back,
and rode him all the way home.

599
00:48:42,600 --> 00:48:44,900
- Isn't that cool?
- That's very cool.

600
00:48:45,400 --> 00:48:49,250
- What is this?
- It's an orca, like Willy.

601
00:48:49,250 --> 00:48:52,150
Randolph gave it to me.
It's from his tribe.

602
00:48:52,150 --> 00:48:53,650
It's beautiful.

603
00:49:01,400 --> 00:49:04,700
Well. You get some rest.
Here.

604
00:49:08,550 --> 00:49:09,800
Sweet dreams.

605
00:49:10,140 --> 00:49:11,250
Night.

